Temporary paralysis of left eyelid which was a symptom of Bells Palsy. At the same time I experienced a very disturbing sensation of having no saliva in mouth or throat. I was completely dry and unable to produce saliva. This is my description of the event: I woke up around 3am with rapid heartbeat, lightheadness, and upon opening my eyes I realized my left eyelid was drooping and I was unable to open it. At the same time I experienced extreme dryness in my mouth and throat where i had absolutely no moisture/saliva and was unable to produce any for approximately 20 minutes. I walked to an emergency, which was just 2 blocks away, to get checked out. I told the attending nurse and physician what my symptoms were. Luckily by the time I was admitted to the ER the symptoms began to dissipate. My eyelid was slightly droopy but moving and i was able to produce saliva again. I explained that I've never experienced symptoms like this before in my life and that I believed this was from the vaccine. I had been experiencing symptoms every day since receiving the shot.... from headaches, to fatigue, to tightness in my chest, a cough, pain in my larynx that towards my chest, pain in my upper left abdomen, strange sensations in my legs, brain fogginess, and some swollen lymph nodes.

60 2021-03-21 confusional state, memory impairment On March 16th at roughly 1:30pm, the patient received his first dose of the COVID19 Moderna vaccine.... Read more
Close
On March 16th at roughly 1:30pm, the patient received his first dose of the COVID19 Moderna vaccine. Afterward, the patient experienced no adverse side effects. About 48 hours later, however, at 2pm on March 18th, the patient's spouse attempted to wake him from a nap. The patient seemed much groggier than normal and his expression appeared vacant. When pressed by his spouse, the patient could not say who he was, or who his wife was. He agreed to travel with his wife to the hospital. At the hospital, a healthcare professional asked the patient who he was. He answered with his correct name. He also correctly identified his spouse by name. But when asked where he was, the patient gave a long and incoherent response. After this initial screening, doctors at the hospital evaluated the patient for a stroke. They ruled this out as a possibility. Next, they suspected the patient's MS lesions may have contributed to his "cognitive event." However, after comparing his 2018 scan to a current scan, they determined this was unlikely the cause. After about 24 hours at the hospital, a neurologist hypothesized that the patient had experienced a seizure. Another doctor at the facility concurred with this assessment. By late Friday (more than 24 hours after the episode), the patient had regained most of their cognitive functioning, though he still experienced mild confusion around the week's events (even preceding the "cognitive event"). Prior to now, the patient has never had a seizure before.

Close
Globus; A spontaneous report was received from a Physician concerning a 60 years old, male patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced globus/Sensation of foreign body. The patient's medical history was not provided. Concomitant product use was not provided by the reporter. The patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch number: 006M20A) on 17 Feb 2021, approximately one day prior to the onset of the symptoms intramuscularly for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 18 Feb 2021, the patient experienced an instance of globus. On 18 Feb 2021, the patient was taken to the emergency room and treated with dexamethasone via intramuscular route and was discharged from the emergency room. No relevant laboratory details were included. Action taken with the drug in response to the events were not reported. The outcome of the event, globus was recovered on 18 Feb 2021.; Reporter's Comments: Very limited information regarding the symptoms has been provided at this time. Further information has been requested.

Neuropathy; Arms very hot this morning; A lot of headache; Chills; Pain in his arm; Swelling in his arm; Couldn't sleep due to headache; Feeling that his head is boiling, very hot inside; This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer and describes the occurrence of NEUROPATHY PERIPHERAL (Neuropathy) in a 60-year-old male patient who received COVID-19 vaccination. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below. Concurrent medical conditions included Neuropathy. Concomitant products included AMLODIPINE for Blood pressure, NABUMETONE (RELAFEN) for Muscle relaxant, GABAPENTIN (NEURONTIN) for Pain in spine, TAMSULOSIN HYDROCHLORIDE (FLOMAX RELIEF) and OMEPRAZOLE for Unevaluable therapy. On 06-Apr-2021, the patient received first dose (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 06-Apr-2021, received first dose (Intramuscular) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On 06-Apr-2021, the patient experienced PAIN IN EXTREMITY (Pain in his arm), PERIPHERAL SWELLING (Swelling in his arm), INSOMNIA (Couldn't sleep due to headache), HEAD DISCOMFORT (Feeling that his head is boiling, very hot inside), HEADACHE (A lot of headache) and CHILLS (Chills). On 07-Apr-2021, the patient experienced FEELING HOT (Arms very hot this morning). On an unknown date, the patient experienced NEUROPATHY PERIPHERAL (Neuropathy) (seriousness criteria medically significant). At the time of the report, NEUROPATHY PERIPHERAL (Neuropathy), PAIN IN EXTREMITY (Pain in his arm), PERIPHERAL SWELLING (Swelling in his arm), INSOMNIA (Couldn't sleep due to headache), HEAD DISCOMFORT (Feeling that his head is boiling, very hot inside), FEELING HOT (Arms very hot this morning), HEADACHE (A lot of headache) and CHILLS (Chills) outcome was unknown. Treatment was not reported/ unknown. Company comment:Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.; Sender's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.
60 2021-04-16 agitation, confusional state, disorientation, excessive sleepiness, delirium In summary this is a 60 year old male who was normal functioning presenting to hospital 4 days follo... Read more
Close
In summary this is a 60 year old male who was normal functioning presenting to hospital 4 days following second moderna COVID-19 vaccination with AKI, Rhabdomyolsis, Confusion/Delirium with agitation, multiple acute brain infarcts, DVT, and multilobar pulmonary embolism. 24 hours following vaccination patient began to become slightly confused while driving his wife to her vaccine appointment. Symptoms progressed and included severe fatigue and muscle aches. Patient was taking tizanidine and oxycodone to manage muscle / body aches which had been prescribed for his chronic back pain issues. Patient was noted to be excessively sleeping, and also had fallen twice between vaccination and hospital presentation. 4 days following vaccination he presented to the emergency department with severe lethargy and confusion. He was admitted with presumption of overdose of medication, given activated charcoal. A CT of the head (4/11/2021) was completed which demonstrated No acute intracranial hemorrhage, extra-axial fluid collection or acute territorial infarct. Suggestion of a chronic lacunar infarct involving the left lentiform nucleus. Regions of low attenuation involving the cerebellar hemispheres, right greater than left, which, allowing for image degradation secondary to patient motion artifact, are likely artifactual in nature; follow-up is recommended to assess for stability/resolution.For first several days patient suffered delirium with agitation, he was disoriented to place and time. CK on admission, 4/11/2021, was 17,086, indicating rhabdo. Creatinine on admission was 4.39, indicating new acute renal failure. Liver enzymes were elevated with AST of 477 and ALT of 218. PT was 10.6, INR 0.99. ABG demonstrated metabolic acidosis with pH of 7.22, co2 45, HCO3 18.4. Over several days his mentation improved however was noted to still need light supplemental oxygenation. Because of the delirium a brain MRI was completed on 4/13/2021, which demonstrated acute ischemic infarcts on DWI sequence noting bilateral, right greater than left, acute cerebellar infarcts. Small acute lacunar infarcts at bilateral basal ganglia/genu internal capsule. Due to the infarcts a stroke workup was completed. Carotid duplex was performed and notable for only small bilateral carotid plaque. Renal ultrasound unremarkable. A CTA of the chest was completed on 4/15/2021 for continued hypoxemia, need for nasal cannula to maintain spo2 saturation. Findings included multilobar pulmonary embolism. I had a (first ever) stroke. I was attempting to take Flecainide for atrial fibrillation to reduce palpitations, the week prior and during the day of the stroke. I tried to take Flecainide twice before in the past few months, but I was unable to tolerate it. When I had the stroke, I didn't realize I was having one since I'm in very good health. I emailed my electro-cardiologist about my symptoms that day and found it difficult to use the appropriate words and reading the email later, I could see a number of mistakes. My ability to comprehend spoken language that day was impaired. I could only keep a few sentences in my head at a time and my attention span was poor as well, like having significant ADHD, which I don't have. I was unable to retain simple amounts of information the day of the stroke. I didn't seek treatment on the day of the stroke since I felt it was more of the side effects I had been experiencing from Flecainide. After going to the hospital I felt good and much improved, cognitively. An ER neurologist said that my stroke was a 2 on a scale of 1 to 42. Over the remainder of March and until this day (April 16, 2021), I have made steady and rapid improvement. I attribute my recovery to the lower level of stroke damage and the fact that I worked out every day with physical exercise and I worked out cognitively by doing a series of activities that I chose myself: reading out loud, reciting poetry and tongue twisters, playing logic and puzzle games on the PC, returning to my writing tasks for work, practicing grammar, and speaking at length with family and friends as a way to practice speaking. I had one appointment with an occupational therapist and two appointments with a speech therapist and have completed assessment. I now feel I am nearly completely recovered with an odd sense of some improvement in certain areas such as heightened mood and quicker connections for noticing practical matters.

No Medical History information was reported. On an unknown date, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On an unknown date, the patient experienced ABNORMAL BEHAVIOUR (Acting really weird) (seriousness criterion hospitalization), IRRITABILITY (Irritable) (seriousness criterion hospitalization) and THINKING ABNORMAL (Wasn't thinking clearly) (seriousness criterion hospitalization). At the time of the report, ABNORMAL BEHAVIOUR (Acting really weird), IRRITABILITY (Irritable) and THINKING ABNORMAL (Wasn't thinking clearly) outcome was unknown. The action taken with mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) was unknown. On 25 Mar 2021, approximately 3 hours post vaccination, the reporter stated the patient lost his mind. The patient barrowed $6,000 for a motorcycle. Road the motorcycle into a snow storm. Went to jail for riding the motorcycle 130 miles per house. Has been scattered brain, incoherent. The reporter stated, the patient has been hospitalized in 3 psychiatric hospitals and at the time of this report, was hospitalized in one. On 21 Apr 2021, the patient was normal for approximately 20 hours but resumed acting weird. The patient experiences brain fog in which he can't talk, had no refluxes, can't move but is able to hear. Treatment information was not provided. Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. This case was linked to (E2B Linked Report). My reaction occurred approximately 12 hrs. following the injection. I awoke on the night of Jan. 8 after rolling over on my right arm where the injection site was. I immediately awakened with sharp burning pain and as I became more awake, I realized that I was confused, slightly disoriented and very diapheretic. I alternated between having a chill to sweating profusely. My head was throbbing as in a migraine and the orbits around my eyes hurt as well. I was extremely nausea to the point of gagging but I had not eaten anything so I did not throw up. Later that night I also at watery diarrhea. All of my joints ached and my pelvic region seemed to hurt more than the rest of my body and joints. When I got up, I found that my equilibrium was off and that I was dizzy. My temperature 100.2 but over the next 2 days it went as high as 102, but continued around 100.8 for several hours. Early in the a.m. I called my PCP service and later spoke with the physician on call. We discussed in depth. At that point, my panic had subsided somewhat and he told me to take Tylenol for my fever and I also had Benadryl available and I took 50 mg. I hydrated myself (I did not have an appetite) but forced my to drink fluids and eat a serving of fresh fruit. By mid-day on 1/9 I was feeling less anxious and was able to sit and watch t.v. I continued to take Tylenol and Benadryl and slept for almost 16 hours. On Sunday I was more improved. Since then, I have continued to feel dizziness and tire very easily. Today, my equilibrium is still off and I have difficulty focusing. I have spoken with my PCP twice this week and I will be going into the Covid research clinic next week as they want to examine me and draw blood samples close to the two week period after the first injection.

69 2021-03-09 restlessness, sleep disorder Because of the absurd character limit in this field, I am putting my adverse reaction statement on t... Read more
Close
Because of the absurd character limit in this field, I am putting my adverse reaction statement on the continuation page. About 10pm, about 9 hours post injection, I was feeling weak and fatigued. I went to bed and was starting to feel chilled, but not shaking. I hopped into bed and turned on my electric blanket in a room that was 75 (from passive solar house heating during the day) and wearing only a T-shirt, sweat shirt, and sweat pants. The first post-vaccination symptom I experienced was when I laid down and my right upper arm (at the point of the injection) was very sore; it was too painful to lie on my right side. The injection area felt hard. I fell asleep about 11pm and woke up about midnight; I am generally a very light sleeper, rarely sleeping more than ~3 hours (most less than) at a time. At 1:30am, I could not sleep so I watched a recorded movie. All the while, I was feeling progressively worse. About 2:30am, I felt really chilled, so I cranked up the electric blanket to its highest setting and put on some heavy wool socks, a pair of long-johns under my sweat pants, put on another heavy sweatshirt over my existing sweatshirt, and placed another blanket on top of my electric blanket: very cold / chilled but not shivering. The movie ended about 3am, and my stomach was excruciatingly aching. I did not feel I could eat anything which I really felt a need to do, but was concerned that I would just vomit. However, I did take two, 500mg Tylenol tablets with a half a glass of water. I might have slept for an hour or so, but was quite restless. I remember looking at the clock at 4:00am. By 5am, it was considering calling 911; my stomach ached so badly. It was then, that I had the feeling / recollection I had this "illness" before. About 5:30am, my stomach symptoms started to ameliorate; by 7:30am, they were gone. However, I still felt miserable. I then wondered whether my stomach symptom was just a concomitant bout with "stomach flu" where I experienced (severe) abdominal cramps and pain; nausea; and low-grade fever. I have had the stomach flu a limited number of times before and, after 6 hours, it all went away: I just had to suck it up in the meantime. Before I filled out this report, I wanted to consider whether my stomach flu was a reaction to the vaccination or incidental to the vaccination. However, after talking with my neighbors and my sister's friend, who also had the Moderna vaccination, three of the four "victims" had similar symptoms to me. Thus, I deduced I did not have a bout with stomach flu. Additionally, a dog walking partner, who is a rescue worker, also noted folks she knew also had similar symptoms with the Moderna vaccine. I then started wondering what kind of artificial cocktail, a.k.a.: antifreeze, was the suspending medium for the vaccine. If this has to be stored at absurdly low temperatures I commonly have negative reactions to artificial chemicals. The minor surgeries I have had are uneventful but for the anesthesia chemical concoction I am given. I commonly takes me more then 2-3 days to detoxify that and feel normal.' As in this case, I pretty much laid in bed for the next 2 days, with no energy or desire to attend to personal issues, including walking my dogs. However, my subclinical temperature was pretty much gone after the second day. The notable soreness in my arm was mostly gone after two days, but the injection point was still sensitive to pressing on top of the injection site: I could still feel it. I have a very high tolerance for pain and have never experienced anything like this. "Pain" from flu, etc., shots rarely, if ever, lasts more than 10-15 minutes post injection. There was definitely something in the suspension media that reacted with my body chemistry / biological processes. I am NOT looking forward to the booster shot; most seem to have a reaction to the second shot that is worse than the first unless their first shot was uneventful and the second shot had considerably milder reactions than my first shot. The next time I will definitely have a bowl or two of jell-O in the refrigerator to help quell any (expected) gut reactions; jell-O has always been a comfort food for me in those situations. What a horribly designed survey. This is next to impossible to complete online. After timing out twice, I had to start over and opted to download the fillable form PDF. Even then, I am not given the option to select the subdirectory _where_ it should be downloaded. Fortunately, I saw the option to open it directly. If you are going to make the "adverse reaction" field so limited, relative to field size and the absurd online time limit, how can you expect meaningful, complete reporting of post-vaccination reactions? This form CANNOT be fully completed in the time allotted without timing out. This is, most certainly, a deterrent to adverse reaction reporting. One has to wonder how many folks just gave up after getting timed out the first time. With this kind of disincentive, how good or complete or meaningful is the adverse data collection procedure? Have you purged all the supporters? They do not like real, accurate, objective data, particularly information that is not consistent what they want to believe or the narrative they want to spin. No respectable scientist or decent journalist would accept third-rate data. How can public interest decisions be made with a shoddy data collection effort?

MY REACTION TO THE FIRST DOSE: In March of 2020 I suffered Covid pneumonia and was on oxygen and too weak and short of breath to work for three months. It took over seven months to return my breathing and strength to baseline. I just checked my lab and I still have IgG antibodies and a negative nasal screen for the virus. One month ago at 9 AM I received the Moderna Vaccine. About 12 hours later I developed shaking chills and a fever of about 103, pain in my arm from the injection, and severe cough and a VERY WATERY RUNNY NOSE with severe post nasal drip which caused aspiration of the discharge. I took Tylenol, Afrin Nasal Spray, and a Dulera inhaler and fell asleep. I woke up at 3 AM and felt well, but at 4 AM I developed an intolerable intractable cough and severe watery nasal discharge lasting about two hours and severe dry heaves from the aspiration. Afrin nasal spray helped somewhat but I was absolutely miserable for two hours. Three days ago I received the one month booster for the Moderna Vaccine at 10AM. My arm began to become painful but it was tolerable and not relieved by Tylenol. Every time I rolled over at night the pain woke me up but I was able to tolerate it. Yesterday I woke up with severe constant chills but my temperature was normal. I felt very hungry and diaphoretic and felt like I had a low blood sugar, and ate a bowl of rice chex cereal. I felt a little better but a half hour later VOMITED everything up. I then felt somewhat better and went to the hospital to make rounds. The nursing staff reported that about half of them called in sick due to the vaccine with severe fatigue, fever, joint pains and headaches. One nurse reported that all her joints felt like they were on fire. Four nursing supervisors also called in sick that day. I then went to my office and my staff said I looked GREEN and insisted I go home. I did not eat anything but while resting I again had SEVERE VOMITING of my breakfast at about noon. When I felt stronger I drove home at about 1:30 PM and fell asleep until about 5 PM, still not having eaten anything nor taking fluids. My arm pain went away. By 7 PM I finally drank some tea and felt stronger and felt like I was not going to die. It seems that those of use who had the Covid in the past do not tolerate the vaccine and suffer severe reactions. I was unable to find any studies with the vaccine given to patients who already have antibodies. This lack of data is a real problem.

Patient started feeling woozy, dizzy, slurring words and fatigued around 11:30am. By the afternoon he was extremely fatigued and barely ate lunch or dinner. He went to bed at 9:30pm. By 1:30am, he woke up and urinated the bed because he couldn't get his urinal in place. He was extremely weak and shaking, and could barely hold his body upright when I used the lift to get him out of bed. He was not making coherent sense when he spoke, though his words and sentences were sensical, it made no sense in context. We sent him to the ER on recommendation of the advice nurse and 4:30am. He returned home in early afternoon, but remained weak for over 2 weeks afterward, slurring words and having trouble lifting his arms, though mental function returned by that same day. The doctors believe that he had a TIA, though no evidence of a clot showed up. They did discover that he has atrial fibrillation, though they had never detected that before on the heart exams following his heart attack.

Patient woke up around 3:30am feeling extremely nauseous, shaking, drenched in sweat but with a normal temperature (97.6, which is normal for him), and feeling overall terrible. Food had tasted weird to him the day before, but he still ate. At 3:30am, he felt like he was having a major allergy attack - lots of phlegm, runny nose and eyes. He spit up a lot of thick phlegm (which can be normal for him, due to IBM). After 15 mins, the sweat and shaking died down, and he felt better enough to think about going to sleep. But 5 minutes later, the nausea returned, and he threw up about 25 mL of black "coffee grounds-like" fluid. (The smell was HORRIBLE). After getting through with that (about 15 minutes), he wretched up more thick mucus with a few flecks of black cells in it. After awhile, he felt okay enough to go back to sleep. Around 6am, he had another major allergy-like attack, but did not vomit. Around 8am, after being awake for awhile, he vomited again with more black liquid, about 50mL this time. He felt weak and horrible and was shaking. At the recommendation of the advice nurse, he was taken to the ER by ambulance. Upon arriving, he waited around an hour for an ER bed. They put him on an IV, did a physical inspection and did blood work. His sodium was a bit low, but in normal range. Potassium levels were fine. He was mentally clear the whole time, but physically very weak. He was kept overnight after a hemochrit test in the afternoon showed low levels of hemoglobin. He was stabilized in the morning, but was barely able to eat anything the whole time. He was meant to get an endoscopy, but they decided to allow him to eat and sent him home after noon bc they hadn't yet been able to schedule him for it and he was in pain and massively hungry. When he got home, he still barely ate, and still isn't eating almost anything a day later. His stool was incredibly black and thick and SMELLY immediately upon arriving home (he had not defecated for 48 hours at that point), and he has not been able to defecate since, which is extremely abnormal (he usually goes each day in the morning upon waking). They believe that he may have bleeding in his stomach or upper GI or esophagus, but we are waiting for an endoscopy later this week. He is still very weak and frail and fatigued.

Spinal cord issue; Weakness; Parkinson's disease flare up; Hallucination; Syncope; Balance disorder; Movement disorder; Abnormal sleep related event; Musculoskeletal disorder; dyskinesia; Back pain; Limb discomfort; Musculoskeletal stiffness; Neck pain; Fall; Confusional state; Abnormal dreams; Orthostatic hypotension; Livedo reticularis; Somnolence; Dizziness postural; Gait disturbance; A spontaneous report was received from a pharmaceutical provider concerning a 75-year- old, male patient, who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced events spinal cord disorder, parkinson's disease flare-up, asthenia, balance disorder, movement disorder, abnormal sleep related event, musculoskeletal disorder, dyskinesia, back pain, limb discomfort, musculoskeletal stiffness, neck pain, hallucination, fall, confusional state, abnormal dreams, orthostatic hypotension, livedo reticularis, somnolence, syncope, dizziness postural and gait disturbance. The patient's medical history included Parkinson's disease, dyskinesia, arthritis, heart disease, spondylitis, body height decreased and two cardiac stent placement. In 2020, after starting Gocovri, the patient experienced hallucinations, falls, balance issues , confusion, jerky movements and weird and intense dreams. The concomitant medications on use included amantadine/gocovri used for dyskinesia associated with Parkinson's disease, levodopa, carbidopa, entacapone, tamsulosin, magnesium, cholecalciferol, vitamin C (ascorbic acid), paracetamol, cetirizine hydrochloride, fluticasone propionate, acetylsalicylic acid, pravastatin, clopidogrel, ropinirole hydrochloride, rasagiline mesylate, macrogol 3350, methyl cellulose, cyanocobalamin and multivitamin, all used for unknown indication. On 20-JAN-2021, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA (Batch/Lot number: unknown) through unknown route of administration for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 25-JAN-2021, patient had gottn worse, had difficulty walking, his legs felt very heavy and he was high stepping when he walked, he could hardly walk, weakness in legs, muscle stiffness and weakness, necak and back pain. Visited doctor. These events were considered to be not resolved. On 17-FEB-2021, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their second of two planned doses of mRNA (Batch/Lot number: unknown) through unknown route of administration for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 22-FEB-2021, patient experienced balance disorder, movement disorder, abnormal sleep related event, musculoskeletal disorder, dyskinesia, back pain, limb discomfort, musculoskeletal stiffness, neck pain, hallucination, fall, confusional state, abnormal dreams, orthostatic hypotension, livedo reticularis, somnolence, syncope, dizziness postural and gait disturbance. On 25-FEB-2021, patient experienced spinal cord disorder, weakness/asthenia and Parkinson's disease flare up/Parkinson's disease. The patient was hospitalized on 25-FEB-2021 and was discharged on 01-MAR-2021. The patient received both scheduled doses of mRNA-1273 prior to the events, therefore action taken with the drug in response to the events was not applicable. The events spinal cord disorder, weakness and Parkinson's disease flare up were recovered on 01-MAR-2021. The outcome of the events balance disorder, movement disorder, abnormal sleep related event, musculoskeletal disorder, dyskinesia, back pain, limb discomfort, musculoskeletal stiffness, neck pain, hallucination, fall, confusional state, abnormal dreams, orthostatic hypotension, livedo reticularis, somnolence, syncope, dizziness postural and gait disturbance were unknown.; Reporter's Comments: Very limited information regarding these events has been provided at this time. Patient's advanced age along with concomitant medications and underlying conditions may have been contributory for the occurrence of the events. No further follow-up information is expected.; Sender's Comments: Very limited information regarding these events has been provided at this time. Patient's advanced age along with concomitant medications and underlying conditions may have been contributory for the occurrence of the events. No further follow-up information is expected.

Anger; High blood pressure; not being himself; Confused; Agitated; Combative, became aggressive; Crying, yelling, clapping; This spontaneous case was reported by a nurse (subsequently medically confirmed) and describes the occurrence of ANGER (Anger), AGGRESSION (Combative, became aggressive) and MENTAL STATUS CHANGES (Crying, yelling, clapping) in a 75-year-old male patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch no. 036A21A) for COVID-19 vaccination. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below. The patient's past medical history included No adverse event (No adverse event history.). Concomitant products included METFORMIN, ATORVASTATIN CALCIUM (LIPITOR), ALLOPURINOL, DOXAZOSIN MESILATE (CARDURA), TELMISARTAN (MICARDIS) and AMLODIPINE. On 10-Mar-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 12-Mar-2021, the patient experienced ANGER (Anger) (seriousness criterion hospitalization), AGGRESSION (Combative, became aggressive) (seriousness criteria medically significant and life threatening), MENTAL STATUS CHANGES (Crying, yelling, clapping) (seriousness criterion medically significant), FEELING ABNORMAL (not being himself), CONFUSIONAL STATE (Confused) and AGITATION (Agitated). On an unknown date, the patient experienced HYPERTENSION (High blood pressure). At the time of the report, ANGER (Anger), AGGRESSION (Combative, became aggressive), MENTAL STATUS CHANGES (Crying, yelling, clapping), HYPERTENSION (High blood pressure), FEELING ABNORMAL (not being himself), CONFUSIONAL STATE (Confused) and AGITATION (Agitated) outcome was unknown. The action taken with mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) was unknown. For mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular), the reporter did not provide any causality assessments. Treatment of these events included Seroquel 400mg once a day. Very limited information regarding the events has been provided at this time. The events were consistent with increased risk of complications associated with elderly age of patient. Further information has been requested. Company assessed the events to be unlikely related to company product.; Sender's Comments: Very limited information regarding the events has been provided at this time. The events were consistent with increased risk of complications associated with elderly age of patient. Further information has been requested. Company assessed the events to be unlikely related to company product.
75 2021-04-13 disorientation On March 4 patient experienced vomiting. Early morning March 5 he fell and landed on his hip after b... Read more
Close
On March 4 patient experienced vomiting. Early morning March 5 he fell and landed on his hip after being disoriented and experienced aches, weakness, and nausea without vomiting throughout the day. On March 6 he experienced excruciating pain in his left hip and went to the local emergency room following guidance from his primary care physician. He was diagnosed with fluid near his hip joint at the hospital and was discharged the same day. The next day, March 7 he was still in pain but able to walk with assistance. On March 8 he got an x-ray from an orthopedic physician and severe arthritis was found. March 10 the severe pain persisted, but he was able to walk with a walker. On March 12 he received a cortisone shot and required emergency medical assistance to get into a personal vehicle with a family member who drove to the appointment. The next few days, the pain persisted, became worse, and spread throughout his body. On March 16 he was transported by emergency medical services to the local emergency room for treatment and was diagnosed with sepsis and pneumonia. On March 18 he was still being treated when he experienced cardiac arrest while being intubated. He was resuscitated and was on a ventilator being treated for a few more days but ultimately succumbed to sepsis on March 30.
